'''Jacob Alexander Roper'''<ref>{{Citation|last=DONG|title=What Language Is This?|date=2018-08-17|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bAp4p9iuo3U|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref> (born January 25, 1987) is an American [[Internet celebrity]] primarily known for hosting the [[Vsauce3]] YouTube channel, which is part of the YouTube channel brand [[Vsauce]]. Jake posts content related to fictional worlds, video games, and science. on his channel<ref name="Vsauce.com">{{Cite web|url = http://www.vsauce.com/img/Vsauce3-jake-bio.pdf|title = Vsauce3 Jake Bio|last =|first =|date =|website = VSauce|archive-url =|archive-date =|dead-url =|access-date =}}</ref> Roper also has a personal side channel "OFFICIALjakeroper"<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/user/OFFICIALjakeroper/|title = Jake Roper|website = YouTube|language = en|access-date = 2017-09-05}}</ref> and frequently hosts on other Vsauce network channels, including DONG (Do Online Now, Guys) and the group channel WeSauce.
== Early life and education == Roper was born on January 25, 1987<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roper|first1=Jake|title=So, my awesome girlfriend @rebeccaaaa just had a singing guerilla come and wish me a happy birthday in front of my whole office.|url=https://twitter.com/jakerawr/status/29989937222782976|website=Twitter|accessdate=22 September 2017|language=en|date=25 January 2011}}</ref> and grew up in [[Evergreen, Colorado]].<ref name="Vsauce.com" /> He attended New York's [[School of Visual Arts]] where he received a degree in film.<ref name="The Daily Dot">{{Cite news|url = https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/vsauce3-jake-roper-interview/|title = Vsauce3: The man, the myth, the legend|date = 2015-10-14|work = The Daily Dot|access-date = 2017-09-05|language = en-US}}</ref> Prior to working on YouTube, Roper used his film degree for various jobs in television and advertising.<ref name="Vsauce.com" /><ref name="The Daily Dot" />
== Career == Before meeting [[Michael Stevens (educator)|Michael Stevens]], Roper hosted a YouTube show called Space Lab,<ref name="The Daily Dot" /> which was a space show for kids.<ref name="Vsauce.com" /> Stevens brought on Roper to edit videos in 2011; in 2012, Roper started uploading on Vsauce3 regularly beginning with the segment ''App All Knight''.<ref name="The Daily Dot" /><ref>{{Citation|last = Vsauce3|title = Rainbow Whale Butt and MORE! - App All Knight #1|date = 2012-09-12|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ag2EpAu1SL4|accessdate = 2017-09-05}}</ref> Over time, Roper began to host all of the shows on Vsauce3, effectively making it his own channel.
Segments on this channel, such as ''Game LÜT'', ''App All Knight'', ''HeadShot'', ''9bit'', and ''Fact Surgery'' have either been discontinued or moved to other Vsauce network channels.{{Citation needed|date = September 2017}} This allowed for Roper to focus on the main content of the channel, which focuses on explanations of the science behind fictional worlds.<ref name="The Daily Dot" /> Over the years, Roper has worked with various celebrities and experts including [[Neil deGrasse Tyson]], [[Bill Nye]], [[Jack Black]], and [[Paul Rudd]].<ref name="The Daily Dot" /><ref>{{Citation|last = Vsauce3|title = Time ft. Neil deGrasse Tyson|date = 2017-03-07|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AORsw8NpN4E|accessdate = 2017-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last = Vsauce3|title = 3 Time Travel Paradoxes!!|date = 2015-01-28|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AOwRb584r1c|accessdate = 2017-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last = Vsauce3|title = 4 STRANGE Paranormal Phenomena! feat. Jack Black|date = 2015-10-12|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nsMxsIZSg08|accessdate = 2017-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last = Vsauce3|title = What Would Happen if You Were Shrunk?|date = 2015-07-14|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xkvo-DrU2gM|accessdate = 2017-09-05}}</ref> In December 2016, Roper collaborated with [[Mark Rober]] to recreate traps from the 1990 film ''[[Home Alone]]'' in a video titled ''"Could You Survive Home Alone?"''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roper|first1=Jake|title=Could You Survive Home Alone?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5NhijmGTwwo|website=YouTube|accessdate=22 September 2017|date=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jake Roper from VSauce Proves the Devastating Effects of the HOME ALONE Booby Traps {{!}} Nerdist|url=http://nerdist.com/jake-roper-from-vsauce-proves-the-devastating-effects-of-the-home-alone-booby-traps/|website=Nerdist|accessdate=22 September 2017|language=en|date=18 December 2016}}</ref><ref name="parade">{{cite web|title=The Best Parts of Vsauce + Win a Vsauce Curiosity Box!|url=https://parade.com/596983/parade/the-best-parts-of-vsauce-win-a-vsauce-curiosity-box/|website=Parade|accessdate=22 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> Roper worked with [[Kurzgesagt – In a Nutshell]] in September 2017 to make a video about Nick Bostrom's [[Nick Bostrom#Simulation argument|Simulation argument]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Kurzgesagt – In a Nutshell|title=Is Reality Real? The Simulation Argument|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tlTKTTt47WE|website=YouTube|accessdate=22 September 2017|date=21 September 2017}}</ref>
On March 31, 2017, Roper announced that he had joined as the new director of production at [[Casey Neistat]]'s company and YouTube channel, [[Beme]] News.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://twitter.com/jakerawr/status/847878454431424512|title = Excited to announce that I've joined my friend @caseyneistat at Beme as director of production.pic.twitter.com/cIISRhwwIH|last = Roper|first = Jake|date = 2017-03-31|website = @jakerawr|access-date = 2017-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jake Roper Of Vsauce3 YouTube Channel Joins Casey Neistat’s CNN-Owned Company Beme - Tubefilter|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/04/03/jake-roper-vsauce3-casey-neistat-beme/|website=Tubefilter|accessdate=22 September 2017|date=3 April 2017}}</ref> However, on January 31, 2018, CNN closed the Beme News division and offered the 22-person team positions in CNN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/01/25/cnn-shuts-down-casey-neistats-beme-but-some-of-its-digital-news-tech-will-live-on/|title=CNN shuts down Casey Neistat’s Beme, but some of its digital news tech will live on|last=Perez|first=Sarah|date=January 25, 2018|website=Tech Crunch|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref>
On September 20, 2018, it was announced that Roper would be hosting the [[YouTube]] Original special ''Could You Survive the Movies''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://realscreen.com/2018/09/20/exclusive-ample-youtube-team-on-could-you-survive-the-movies-special/|title=Exclusive: AMPLE, YouTube team on "Could you Survive the Movies" special|last=Blichert|first=Frederick|date=20 September 2018|website=Realscreen|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2018}}</ref>
== Personal life == On November 25, 2015, Roper announced on his side channel that he had a rare form of cancer called a [[sarcoma]].<ref>{{Citation|last = Jake Roper|title = I Need to Tell You Something.|date = 2015-11-25|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LpqnX4Who2Q|accessdate = 2017-09-05}}</ref> In June 2016, he announced that test readings had come back indicating that the cancer was gone.<ref>{{Citation|last = Jake Roper|title = I Have a Secret|date = 2016-06-07|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p91-GhjgeEU|accessdate = 2017-09-05}}</ref>
